AFRICAN SWINE FEVER IN SOUTH AFRICA in the African swine fever controlled area
----------------------------------------------------------
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: December 1998)
Emergency report
Information received on 8 Aug 2001 from Dr Emily Mmamakgaba Mogajane, Chief
Director, Agricultural Production, National Department of Agriculture,
Pretoria:
Report date: 8 Aug 2001.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 17 Jul 2001.
Outbreaks:
No. of outbreaks 1 farm
Location: Thabazimbi magisterial district (24 deg. 44 min. S - 26 deg. 40
min. E), Northern Province
Description of affected population: domestic pigs.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
sui / 30 / 23 / 23 / 7 / 0
Diagnosis: the owner of the pigs started noticing deaths in his pigs on 17
Jul 2001. He notified the local Animal Health Technician on 29 July, and on
the same day samples were taken and sent to the laboratory for confirmation.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Exotic Diseases Division of the
Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation on bone marrow culture and
polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: contact between domestic pigs and
warthog (_Phacochoerus aethiopicus_).
B. Mode of spread: direct contact.
C. Other epidemiological details: this outbreak has occurred within the
African swine fever controlled area of South Africa.
Control measures: normal zoosanitary measures have been instituted:
- all pigs on the farm have been destroyed;
- the farm has been placed under quarantine until the end of October 2001;
- no marketing of pigs from this area will be allowed for local or export
purposes.
As this outbreak has occurred within the African swine fever controlled
area of South Africa, it does not affect the export of animals and animal
products from non-controlled areas.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Spread from warthogs happens from time to time, and it appears as if there
may be no spread to other farms. In some of the references cited above,
however, ASF has been devastating -- often resulting in the loss of 80% of
the pig population in affected areas. - Mod.PC
